41
00:02:10,120 --> 00:02:10,560
mechanics.

42
00:02:11,220 --> 00:02:14,383
And this is in terms of our project Lost Words Beyond the

43
00:02:14,403 --> 00:02:20,688
Page, which is a atmospheric puzzler game half set inside

44
00:02:20,708 --> 00:02:21,709
the pages of a diary.

45
00:02:22,293 --> 00:02:25,575
and half set in a fantasy world called Astoria.

46
00:02:26,136 --> 00:02:28,257
It's about this young girl called Izzy

47
00:02:28,337 --> 00:02:29,918
who's aspiring to be a writer

48
00:02:30,338 --> 00:02:32,700
and her gran is helping to mentor her.

49
00:02:33,080 --> 00:02:35,802
But when her gran gets ill and has a stroke,

50
00:02:36,282 --> 00:02:40,105
Izzy starts to use the fantasy world of Astoria

51
00:02:40,145 --> 00:02:42,947
that she's writing about as a means of coping

52
00:02:43,007 --> 00:02:44,688
with what's going on in the real world.

53
00:02:45,449 --> 00:02:48,031
So let's take a quick look at the trailer

54
00:02:48,051 --> 00:02:49,431
so you can see what the game's all about.

55
00:02:52,935 --> 00:02:57,999
So as you can see here, we're running along the words and using them as platforms, but you can also

56
00:02:58,899 --> 00:03:02,982
drag them around the screen and use them to solve different puzzles.

57
00:03:04,524 --> 00:03:13,050
Also at some points to make choices that affect the fantasy world, which we then transition into here.

58
00:03:15,102 --> 00:03:18,664
So in the historian section, you're not walking on the words,

59
00:03:18,944 --> 00:03:22,625
but you are using them to interact with the world in different ways.

60
00:03:32,009 --> 00:03:35,431
We've also got this word book with you at the top left of the screen there,

61
00:03:35,871 --> 00:03:38,532
and that allows you to carry some of the words with you,

62
00:03:38,592 --> 00:03:41,593
so you can use them at different points throughout the level.

63
00:03:47,823 --> 00:03:53,204
So the challenge that we've been looking to overcome

64
00:03:53,364 --> 00:03:56,265
has been how to use words as game mechanics

65
00:03:56,385 --> 00:03:58,846
to help tell an emotionally moving story,

66
00:03:59,426 --> 00:04:03,107
but while also remaining localizable for other languages.

67
00:04:05,308 --> 00:04:07,108
There has been other games that have done

68
00:04:07,148 --> 00:04:10,049
interesting things with text, including Typo Man,

69
00:04:10,429 --> 00:04:14,350
Epistory, Today I Die, Typewriter, and also Letters,

70
00:04:14,370 --> 00:04:16,331
which is a game that's currently in development.

71
00:04:17,698 --> 00:04:20,500
on show at GDC here if you get a chance to check that out.

72
00:04:23,002 --> 00:04:25,964
We've tried to tackle the problem in three different ways.

73
00:04:26,524 --> 00:04:29,906
Firstly, by ensuring that the gameplay and story help

74
00:04:29,946 --> 00:04:30,607
serve each other.

75
00:04:33,429 --> 00:04:36,711
Then by trying to use metaphors to make the gameplay more

76
00:04:36,751 --> 00:04:37,792
powerful and moving.

77
00:04:40,574 --> 00:04:43,556
And also by using localization to try and allow

78
00:04:43,576 --> 00:04:45,577
as many people as possible to experience

79
00:04:45,617 --> 00:04:46,898
the game in their own language.

80
00:04:50,325 --> 00:04:53,147
So for us, we've tried to give the gameplay and story

81
00:04:53,287 --> 00:04:55,768
equal importance, which sometimes has meant

82
00:04:56,008 --> 00:04:59,130
leaving a particular narrative beat on the shelf

83
00:04:59,211 --> 00:05:01,332
if we couldn't find the gameplay to fit with it,

84
00:05:01,452 --> 00:05:04,154
or sometimes icing a really cool mechanic

85
00:05:04,534 --> 00:05:06,895
because it didn't work with the narrative.

86
00:05:07,616 --> 00:05:11,038
And while it was a shame to lose those individual parts,

87
00:05:11,458 --> 00:05:13,600
it makes the experience stronger

88
00:05:13,740 --> 00:05:15,141
and more cohesive as a whole.

89
00:05:18,425 --> 00:05:21,127
So here's the most exciting thing that we realized

90
00:05:21,488 --> 00:05:22,208
when making the game.

91
00:05:24,010 --> 00:05:25,511
Anything that we ask the player to do

92
00:05:26,692 --> 00:05:28,254
is something that they will feel.

93
00:05:28,894 --> 00:05:31,276
And so therefore, it carries meaning.

94
00:05:32,958 --> 00:05:35,300
So let's take a look at an example of this.

95
00:05:36,021 --> 00:05:38,903
On this level, in one sense, you solve the simple puzzle

96
00:05:38,963 --> 00:05:40,885
to turn the words into platforms to get

97
00:05:40,905 --> 00:05:44,008
to the tear on the side of the screen there to progress.

98
00:05:46,495 --> 00:05:48,036
but there's a real meaning that we're driving at

99
00:05:48,196 --> 00:05:50,137
by organizing the level this way.

100
00:05:50,977 --> 00:05:53,859
Izzy has aspirations, she's trying to order the future,

101
00:05:53,979 --> 00:05:57,520
so players putting the words in place and leading upwards

102
00:05:57,941 --> 00:06:00,342
is a way of emphasizing that narrative expression.

103
00:06:03,463 --> 00:06:06,945
Here's another example where we see and experience

104
00:06:07,005 --> 00:06:09,666
how Izzy is overwriting her memories of the past

105
00:06:10,026 --> 00:06:11,847
and we're making the player responsible for that.

106
00:06:13,684 --> 00:06:16,126
They must overwrite these memories by moving across them

107
00:06:16,226 --> 00:06:17,127
in order to progress.

108
00:06:18,187 --> 00:06:21,190
We're trying to put the player in the same emotional space

109
00:06:21,270 --> 00:06:21,630
as Izzy.

110
00:06:22,350 --> 00:06:24,992
So here she's worried about her memories of her gran,

111
00:06:25,052 --> 00:06:28,555
and we're seeing them replaced with images of her gran

112
00:06:28,755 --> 00:06:29,836
sick in her hospital bed.

113
00:06:32,297 --> 00:06:35,540
This level actually came about as a bit of an accident of,

114
00:06:36,080 --> 00:06:38,422
I was playing around in Unity with kinematic physics,

115
00:06:39,063 --> 00:06:41,064
and then when I jumped on the sentences,

116
00:06:41,165 --> 00:06:42,846
they all fell away from underneath me,

117
00:06:43,747 --> 00:06:45,708
which really surprised me.

118
00:06:45,848 --> 00:06:49,071
And so then when we had the narrative beat

119
00:06:49,451 --> 00:06:51,433
of Izzy's Gran having her stroke,

120
00:06:51,473 --> 00:06:53,535
which is an unexpected moment in the story,

121
00:06:53,895 --> 00:06:56,357
we felt that that would actually be a really good fit

122
00:06:56,697 --> 00:07:00,961
of this point of the story with that particular mechanic.

123
00:07:02,332 --> 00:07:05,413
This narrative beat is about inversion of Izzy's world

124
00:07:05,733 --> 00:07:08,394
and the profound confusion that her grand stroke causes.

125
00:07:08,935 --> 00:07:10,715
And the delivery of this beat through gameplay,

126
00:07:11,015 --> 00:07:12,656
through the letters falling away,

127
00:07:13,296 --> 00:07:15,317
is an eloquent expression of that meaning.

128
00:07:16,538 --> 00:07:18,899
Izzy's world is dramatically disrupted.

129
00:07:23,620 --> 00:07:27,405
So finally, with our localization system,

130
00:07:28,206 --> 00:07:30,128
as you can see here, even a single word

131
00:07:30,168 --> 00:07:32,471
can be quite a different length in different languages,

132
00:07:32,511 --> 00:07:34,934
which poses quite a problem for us in a game

133
00:07:34,994 --> 00:07:37,937
when even changing a word by a couple of letters

134
00:07:38,418 --> 00:07:39,379
can break a level.

135
00:07:41,555 --> 00:07:45,057
So when one of our original programmers started with us, Audrey Prophet,

136
00:07:45,497 --> 00:07:50,979
one of her first tasks was to come up with a scaling collision box

137
00:07:50,999 --> 00:07:53,460
that adjusts automatically based on the length of the text,

138
00:07:53,820 --> 00:07:57,322
because we were finding we were spending hours tuning things,

139
00:07:57,342 --> 00:07:58,943
and then we would change a couple of words,

140
00:07:58,983 --> 00:08:00,183
and you'd have to go back and redo it.

141
00:08:00,603 --> 00:08:02,284
So this saved us a lot of time.

142
00:08:03,739 --> 00:08:06,840
Another one of the programmers on the team,

143
00:08:06,900 --> 00:08:10,902
Khan Bianco, is the one who wrote the smart localization

144
00:08:10,963 --> 00:08:11,323
system.

145
00:08:12,403 --> 00:08:15,545
So this allows us to make changes

146
00:08:15,765 --> 00:08:17,246
on a per-language basis.

147
00:08:17,886 --> 00:08:21,708
So we can see here that we can switch between the languages

148
00:08:21,768 --> 00:08:22,269
on the fly.

149
00:08:23,029 --> 00:08:25,811
And you can see some of the different problems we've got.

150
00:08:26,051 --> 00:08:29,713
Sometimes, like here in Spanish, some of the draggable words

151
00:08:29,753 --> 00:08:32,655
are appearing over the text on the page.

152
00:08:33,986 --> 00:08:36,527
And then in other languages like German,

153
00:08:36,968 --> 00:08:39,689
the three draggable words aren't appearing on a single line

154
00:08:39,749 --> 00:08:41,810
like they should be, but the system allows us

155
00:08:41,850 --> 00:08:44,432
to move all those around and change it per language

156
00:08:44,632 --> 00:08:45,913
and then save that out.

157
00:08:48,188 --> 00:08:51,030
This is our localization spreadsheet here.

158
00:08:51,250 --> 00:08:53,852
So you can see the different languages down the bottom.

159
00:08:54,632 --> 00:08:56,453
And if we zoom in, you can see that we

160
00:08:56,653 --> 00:09:00,435
use different parentheses to denote

161
00:09:00,775 --> 00:09:02,016
different types of words.

162
00:09:02,436 --> 00:09:04,858
So the localizers can just move these around,

163
00:09:05,578 --> 00:09:07,759
and then the game will automatically pick it up.

164
00:09:08,620 --> 00:09:12,922
And so if we needed more or less interactive words

165
00:09:13,062 --> 00:09:14,423
in a different language, or they needed

166
00:09:14,443 --> 00:09:16,304
to be at a different place in the sentence,

167
00:09:16,384 --> 00:09:17,384
they can easily do that.

168
00:09:18,225 --> 00:09:21,948
So here we've got the square brackets denoting a draggable word

169
00:09:22,608 --> 00:09:25,771
and curly brackets denoting a blue word

170
00:09:26,331 --> 00:09:29,874
that's one of our trigger words that causes something to happen when you stand on it.

171
00:09:30,955 --> 00:09:34,298
So we can see this system in action here

172
00:09:34,658 --> 00:09:38,802
by dragging one of our smart sentence prefabs into the scene

173
00:09:39,102 --> 00:09:43,025
and then you literally just paste the text tag in and it auto-populates it

174
00:09:43,045 --> 00:09:45,768
with all the different types of words.

175
00:09:47,204 --> 00:09:49,867
And so that saves us a lot of time,

176
00:09:50,127 --> 00:09:53,190
and it makes it a lot more doable

177
00:09:53,671 --> 00:09:58,055
for translating the game to lots of different languages.

178
00:09:58,135 --> 00:10:00,558
Because with it being a word-based game,

179
00:10:00,838 --> 00:10:03,481
it makes a big impact for people if they can play it

180
00:10:03,661 --> 00:10:04,722
in their own language.

181
00:10:08,938 --> 00:10:11,300
To summarize, we've used text in unusual ways

182
00:10:11,340 --> 00:10:13,902
to form word-based gameplay through metaphors

183
00:10:14,002 --> 00:10:15,724
and careful planning, but with puzzles

184
00:10:15,764 --> 00:10:17,905
that can still be translated to different languages.

185
00:10:19,626 --> 00:10:22,028
But ours isn't the first or only way of doing this.

186
00:10:25,271 --> 00:10:26,812
This slide always takes a little while to load.

187
00:10:26,832 --> 00:10:27,592
I think that's going to cut you.

188
00:10:27,612 --> 00:10:27,973
There we go.

189
00:10:28,253 --> 00:10:32,176
So perhaps you might like to try using gameplay or metaphors

190
00:10:32,516 --> 00:10:35,238
or using text to provide an unusual mechanic

191
00:10:35,318 --> 00:10:36,559
for your next project.

192
