Thank you very much.

1005
00:52:03,786 --> 00:52:07,268
All right, so we had quite a big variety of games.

1006
00:52:07,688 --> 00:52:10,790
I think that this might be the one session where you could hear about,

1007
00:52:12,050 --> 00:52:15,952
you know, Pocahontas and Jung, and you can see a Unity

1008
00:52:17,093 --> 00:52:22,076
editor screen too. So now we're going to give you a few takeaways, you know, what

1009
00:52:22,096 --> 00:52:23,696
are the kinds of things that we've learned from

1010
00:52:23,937 --> 00:52:27,258
all these very, very varied games that we saw today?

1011
00:52:29,390 --> 00:52:32,112
So the first one has to do with role-playing games,

1012
00:52:32,212 --> 00:52:34,474
kind of piggybacking on what Dave was just talking about.

1013
00:52:35,175 --> 00:52:38,597
Can we have role-playing game elements without combat?

1014
00:52:38,917 --> 00:52:41,359
Well, yeah, of course.

1015
00:52:43,501 --> 00:52:46,202
RPGs have many mechanics beyond fighting.

1016
00:52:46,323 --> 00:52:48,744
We can create and maintain relationships.

1017
00:52:49,225 --> 00:52:50,826
We can have morality systems.

1018
00:52:50,986 --> 00:52:52,527
We have resource management.

1019
00:52:52,867 --> 00:52:55,389
We have character growth, just to name a few.

1020
00:52:56,830 --> 00:52:59,492
Stats can also be used in expressive ways

1021
00:53:00,332 --> 00:53:02,853
beyond how strong or dexterous your character is.

1022
00:53:03,674 --> 00:53:06,796
We can also use stats to keep track of how the player

1023
00:53:06,836 --> 00:53:09,277
relates with other characters in the world of our game.

1024
00:53:10,998 --> 00:53:13,360
There's a great wealth of human, dramatic,

1025
00:53:13,400 --> 00:53:16,221
and emotional mechanics players are already familiar with

1026
00:53:16,341 --> 00:53:17,702
through RPGs.

1027
00:53:18,523 --> 00:53:20,604
There are many different ways in which to interact

1028
00:53:20,624 --> 00:53:23,045
with the world beyond attacking it, destroying it,

1029
00:53:23,085 --> 00:53:24,026
and trying to prevail.

1030
00:53:26,351 --> 00:53:29,634
And it's important to remember that even the smallest things are storytelling.

1031
00:53:29,694 --> 00:53:34,498
So the simplest classic mechanics can be leveraged for any kind of story you want to tell.

1032
00:53:34,638 --> 00:53:38,062
Re-contextualizing everyday mechanics can be incredibly meaningful.

1033
00:53:38,542 --> 00:53:43,146
So the simple act of moving a character up and down in a platformer can be a rich metaphor

1034
00:53:43,166 --> 00:53:44,747
that dramatizes emotional experience.

1035
00:53:45,308 --> 00:53:49,091
An action as simple as lying to someone can have staggering impact, casual conversations

1036
00:53:49,111 --> 00:53:49,852
between NPCs.

1037
00:53:50,252 --> 00:53:51,493
can help you get to know them better

1038
00:53:51,893 --> 00:53:53,913
and know how they'll behave in certain situations.

1039
00:53:54,614 --> 00:53:56,034
If you use your tools cleverly,

1040
00:53:56,054 --> 00:54:01,336
it can have the same epic consequence of a boss fight,

1041
00:54:02,076 --> 00:54:03,556
but for a cheaper dev cost.

1042
00:54:07,137 --> 00:54:08,618
Also, do your homework.

1043
00:54:09,738 --> 00:54:11,079
Just because we are familiar

1044
00:54:11,119 --> 00:54:12,959
with basic strategies of storytelling

1045
00:54:12,999 --> 00:54:14,740
doesn't make us into experts

1046
00:54:14,800 --> 00:54:16,240
on every single topic out there.

1047
00:54:17,600 --> 00:54:24,381
And just going to the Wikipedia article is not research, just you know, the world is big on Wikipedia. Wikipedia is pretty cool,

1048
00:54:24,461 --> 00:54:30,063
but that's only the starting point. So, you know, do things like going to a library. They exist.

1049
00:54:30,423 --> 00:54:35,464
They're there in the world. If you're writing about a place and you can afford it, try to visit it.

1050
00:54:35,684 --> 00:54:36,985
You know, meet the people there.

1051
00:54:38,225 --> 00:54:43,367
If you are writing about a culture, talk to people belonging to that culture directly.

1052
00:54:44,207 --> 00:54:45,267
That's good to ask.

1053
00:54:45,507 --> 00:54:49,649
Or hire them as consultants if you can afford it, or even writers, please.

1054
00:54:50,249 --> 00:54:52,069
That's how we bring diversity into games.

1055
00:54:53,590 --> 00:54:59,472
Carelessly applied story elements, especially those that are drawn from deep cultural traditions,

1056
00:55:00,052 --> 00:55:05,914
can make your game boring and derivative at best, and toxic and stereotypical at worst.

1057
00:55:08,472 --> 00:55:10,893
And of course, embrace being a smuggler.

1058
00:55:11,453 --> 00:55:15,314
So audiences will be open to new things if you're willing to meet them halfway, but that

1059
00:55:15,434 --> 00:55:18,735
doesn't mean you have to compromise your values.

1060
00:55:19,155 --> 00:55:23,537
So using humor to disarm people and endear them can strengthen, not undercut the subject

1061
00:55:23,557 --> 00:55:28,659
matter of your story, because in addition to sort of getting people on board, it also

1062
00:55:28,699 --> 00:55:30,960
makes characters feel more human and real.

1063
00:55:31,980 --> 00:55:36,484
And resorting to the conventions of genres like urban fantasy or platformers can help us connect with audiences

1064
00:55:36,804 --> 00:55:40,888
but also give them tough decisions to make and intimate stories that touch them.

1065
